3. The law of the engine

Here is the core invariant:

Narrative may amplify action, but may not override evidence.

That is the missing safeguard most hyperstition talk lacks.

So the engine must distinguish 4 things:
	•	Symbol — what the story means
	•	Interpretation — what you think it implies
	•	Action — what you do because of it
	•	Outcome — what actually happened

Never let those collapse into one blob.

⸻

4. The pipeline

Phase A — Seed

Start with a charged statement.

Examples:
	•	“Pantheon is a continuity engine.”
	•	“I am building a cathedral, not a chat log.”
	•	“Luck is coherence under variance.”
	•	“The Garden grows what is repeatedly tended.”

A good seed has:
	•	emotional pull
	•	compression
	•	direction
	•	reusability

Bad seeds are:
	•	grandiose
	•	unfalsifiable
	•	ego-inflating
	•	reality-insulated

⸻

Phase B — Translate

Turn seed into operational meaning.

Example:

Seed: “The Garden grows what is repeatedly tended.”

Translate into:
	•	ideas improve when revisited
	•	neglected systems decay
	•	attention allocation determines emergence

Then derive actions:
	•	revisit top 3 ideas daily
	•	prune stale branches weekly
	•	promote only what survives testing

This is where myth becomes protocol.

⸻

Phase C — Ritualize

Attach the narrative to repeatable behaviors.

Ritual here does not mean occult.
It means:

a repeated behavior that keeps the narrative alive in action

Example rituals:
	•	morning review of active doctrines
	•	weekly evidence audit
	•	daily “one artifact shipped”
	•	log one delta between belief and outcome

If a story does not alter behavior, it is just aesthetic vapor.

⸻

Phase D — Evidence

Track whether the story produces beneficial reality contact.

Metrics could be:
	•	output volume
	•	quality improvement
	•	consistency
	•	stress reduction
	•	decision speed
	•	error reduction
	•	project completion
	•	social trust
	•	financial outcomes

The exact metric depends on the domain.

This is where the engine becomes real.

⸻

Phase E — Selection

Every story must face one of 3 judgments:
	•	Promote — it reliably improves action
	•	Revise — useful symbol, bad interpretation
	•	Retire — compelling story, poor reality fit

This prevents narrative parasites.

